0: A serious public debate about the validity of astrology?  A serious believer
1: in the White House?  Two of them?  Give me a break.  What stifled my laughter
2: is that the image fits.  Reagan has always exhibited a fey indifference toward
3: science.  Facts, like numbers, roll off his back.  And we've all come to
4: accept it.  This time it was stargazing that became a serious issue....Not
5: that long ago, it was Reagan's support of Creationism....Creationists actually
6: got equal time with evolutionists.  The public was supposed to be open-minded
7: to the claims of paleontologists and fundamentalists, as if the two were
8: scientific colleagues....It has been clear for a long time that the president
9: is averse to science...In general, these attitudes fall onto friendly American
10: turf....But at the outer edges, this skepticism about science easily turns
11: into a kind of naive acceptance of nonscience, or even nonsense.  The same
12: people who doubt experts can also believe any quackery, from the benefits of

13: laetrile to eye of newt to the movment of planets.  We lose the capacity to
14: make rational -- scientific -- judgments.  It's all the same.
15: -- Ellen Goodman, The Boston Globe Newspaper Company-Washington Post Writers
